WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:07.365 align:middle line:90%


00:00:07.365 --> 00:00:12.766 align:middle line:90%
[THEME MUSIC]

00:00:12.766 --> 00:00:24.931 align:middle line:90%


00:00:24.931 --> 00:00:27.430 align:middle line:10%
>>GEORGE NOORY: Well, welcome
to another edition and "Beyond

00:00:27.430 --> 00:00:28.230 align:middle line:10%
Belief".

00:00:28.230 --> 00:00:30.800 align:middle line:10%
I'm George Noory, and we have
a very special guest for you

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:34.430 align:middle line:10%
on a topic that's very dear
to my heart, of course.

00:00:34.430 --> 00:00:36.770 align:middle line:84%
What happens when the
power grid goes down?

00:00:36.770 --> 00:00:40.020 align:middle line:84%
But David Adair is with us,
the "Rocket Man", of course.

00:00:40.020 --> 00:00:41.540 align:middle line:90%
He's a great researcher.

00:00:41.540 --> 00:00:43.830 align:middle line:84%
He's been studying
this for years.

00:00:43.830 --> 00:00:46.500 align:middle line:84%
And as a matter of fact,
when he was a little boy,

00:00:46.500 --> 00:00:49.740 align:middle line:84%
he started dabbling in
rockets and things like that.

00:00:49.740 --> 00:00:50.990 align:middle line:90%
And he'll tell you about that.

00:00:50.990 --> 00:00:52.530 align:middle line:90%
David, welcome to the program.

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:53.190 align:middle line:90%
>>DAVID ADAIR: Thanks, George.

00:00:53.190 --> 00:00:53.990 align:middle line:90%
Good to be here.

00:00:53.990 --> 00:00:59.590 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How old were you
when all this started for you?

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:01.850 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: About when
memory starts--

00:01:01.850 --> 00:01:04.459 align:middle line:84%
probably when I was
about four or five.

00:01:04.459 --> 00:01:05.835 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Four or
five years old--

00:01:05.835 --> 00:01:06.634 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:01:06.634 --> 00:01:08.843 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --you started
dabbling in rocketry and stuff

00:01:08.843 --> 00:01:09.642 align:middle line:90%
like that?

00:01:09.642 --> 00:01:10.670 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:01:10.670 --> 00:01:12.230 align:middle line:10%
When I first started,
there was just

00:01:12.230 --> 00:01:15.200 align:middle line:10%
little toy rockets that
was just sitting there,

00:01:15.200 --> 00:01:16.550 align:middle line:10%
and I can't have that.

00:01:16.550 --> 00:01:18.030 align:middle line:10%
They've got to move.

00:01:18.030 --> 00:01:21.560 align:middle line:84%
So I had my oldest brother take
a rock that I tied a string to,

00:01:21.560 --> 00:01:23.510 align:middle line:84%
and he threw it
over this tree limb.

00:01:23.510 --> 00:01:25.010 align:middle line:84%
And I tied the
string to the rocket,

00:01:25.010 --> 00:01:26.760 align:middle line:84%
and I could pull on the
string and watch the rocket--

00:01:26.760 --> 00:01:27.885 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You pulled
it up, right?

00:01:27.885 --> 00:01:29.634 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, I'm
only like four or five.

00:01:29.634 --> 00:01:31.710 align:middle line:84%
My brother, what he
was impressed with

00:01:31.710 --> 00:01:34.580 align:middle line:84%
was I figured out how to
tie a string to a rock

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:37.450 align:middle line:84%
and get the string
over the limb.

00:01:37.450 --> 00:01:41.990 align:middle line:84%
But by that time I
was 11, I had read

00:01:41.990 --> 00:01:45.350 align:middle line:84%
enough to where I could start
implementing flying rockets.

00:01:45.350 --> 00:01:47.850 align:middle line:84%
And I started out
with solid rockets,

00:01:47.850 --> 00:01:49.475 align:middle line:84%
and then moved on
up to liquid fuel.

00:01:49.475 --> 00:01:51.350 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And your parents
let you play around

00:01:51.350 --> 00:01:52.100 align:middle line:90%
with this stuff?

00:01:52.100 --> 00:01:53.725 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, that's
the amazing part.

00:01:53.725 --> 00:01:55.920 align:middle line:84%
Well, I was really
good at mechanics.

00:01:55.920 --> 00:01:57.990 align:middle line:90%
My dad was a mechanic.

00:01:57.990 --> 00:02:01.290 align:middle line:84%
My dad was a Lee
Patty's mechanic,

00:02:01.290 --> 00:02:05.450 align:middle line:84%
and so I had enormous
workshops to work with.

00:02:05.450 --> 00:02:07.840 align:middle line:84%
And the first engine
I ever overhauled

00:02:07.840 --> 00:02:11.480 align:middle line:84%
was a 426 Chrysler hemi
engine, and that thing

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:13.670 align:middle line:84%
had two four barrels and
about 900 horsepower.

00:02:13.670 --> 00:02:15.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's
a monster engine.

00:02:15.170 --> 00:02:16.670 align:middle line:84%
How old were you
when you did that?

00:02:16.670 --> 00:02:18.530 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: I was 11 and 1/2.

00:02:18.530 --> 00:02:19.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Jesus.

00:02:19.430 --> 00:02:21.514 align:middle line:84%
How did you even fit into
the engine to get to it?

00:02:21.514 --> 00:02:22.930 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: It was
just about-- well,

00:02:22.930 --> 00:02:24.690 align:middle line:84%
the Hohner weighs
about as much as I did.

00:02:24.690 --> 00:02:27.356 align:middle line:84%
I had to get another mechanic to
help me pick it out and line it

00:02:27.356 --> 00:02:28.490 align:middle line:90%
with the cylinders.

00:02:28.490 --> 00:02:31.389 align:middle line:84%
But once I got that part done,
it was just assembling it.

00:02:31.389 --> 00:02:32.930 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So you were
very intelligent

00:02:32.930 --> 00:02:36.710 align:middle line:84%
when it had to do with
technology and rocketry.

00:02:36.710 --> 00:02:39.440 align:middle line:84%
Did you ever make something
that blew up on the launchpad?

00:02:39.440 --> 00:02:42.050 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Oh lord, it's
more the other way around,

00:02:42.050 --> 00:02:43.610 align:middle line:90%
did I have anything that worked?

00:02:43.610 --> 00:02:45.480 align:middle line:90%
Most of it was blowing up.

00:02:45.480 --> 00:02:47.510 align:middle line:84%
I'm lucky I've got
all my fingers.

00:02:47.510 --> 00:02:49.190 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I was going to say.

00:02:49.190 --> 00:02:50.060 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: I had no--

00:02:50.060 --> 00:02:52.030 align:middle line:84%
I was quick to get
out of the way.

00:02:52.030 --> 00:02:55.820 align:middle line:84%
But yeah, I had a
lot of explosions.

00:02:55.820 --> 00:02:57.300 align:middle line:90%
Some of them were spectacular.

00:02:57.300 --> 00:03:01.010 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What was your very
first successful rocket engine,

00:03:01.010 --> 00:03:03.830 align:middle line:84%
where you launched
an actual rocket?

00:03:03.830 --> 00:03:11.360 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I was 13 years old,
and this one was really good.

00:03:11.360 --> 00:03:14.990 align:middle line:84%
It was about-- almost
as tall as I was.

00:03:14.990 --> 00:03:17.140 align:middle line:84%
About 4 and 1/2 feet
tall, five-foot tall.

00:03:17.140 --> 00:03:19.080 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Made out of
what, paper and balsa?

00:03:19.080 --> 00:03:19.880 align:middle line:90%
Or--

00:03:19.880 --> 00:03:20.630 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Steel.

00:03:20.630 --> 00:03:21.095 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Steel?

00:03:21.095 --> 00:03:21.560 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yes.

00:03:21.560 --> 00:03:23.268 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It was the
real deal, wasn't it?

00:03:23.268 --> 00:03:26.000 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, I skipped
right-- drive well,

00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:29.180 align:middle line:84%
I used the SS rockets,
the little model rockets.

00:03:29.180 --> 00:03:30.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I used to do that too.

00:03:30.510 --> 00:03:31.310 align:middle line:90%
I loved them.

00:03:31.310 --> 00:03:34.010 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: OK, I use those for
wind direction, windstream--

00:03:34.010 --> 00:03:35.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You shoot them
first, the little parachutes

00:03:35.650 --> 00:03:36.440 align:middle line:90%
would come out.

00:03:36.440 --> 00:03:37.250 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I'd shoot them up, see
the drift, take the stopwatch,

00:03:37.250 --> 00:03:39.410 align:middle line:90%
and calculate the upper winds.

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:43.060 align:middle line:84%
I wrote a letter to Verness
and told him some things

00:03:43.060 --> 00:03:44.060 align:middle line:90%
he can do to improve it.

00:03:44.060 --> 00:03:46.282 align:middle line:84%
I didn't tell him
that I was just

00:03:46.282 --> 00:03:47.490 align:middle line:90%
using them for wind trackers.

00:03:47.490 --> 00:03:49.766 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That company is
still here in Colorado.

00:03:49.766 --> 00:03:50.890 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, yeah, it is.

00:03:50.890 --> 00:03:52.310 align:middle line:90%
And I talked to Verne.

00:03:52.310 --> 00:03:53.284 align:middle line:90%
He's still alive.

00:03:53.284 --> 00:03:54.200 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Is he really?

00:03:54.200 --> 00:03:55.000 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:03:55.000 --> 00:03:57.390 align:middle line:84%
He's up in age now, but I
was able to talk to him.

00:03:57.390 --> 00:03:58.190 align:middle line:90%
Really nice guy.

00:03:58.190 --> 00:04:02.620 align:middle line:84%
But he sent me a an awful
lot of motors and rockets,

00:04:02.620 --> 00:04:04.430 align:middle line:90%
and I'd critique them for him.

00:04:04.430 --> 00:04:07.310 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How high up did
this first rocket go?

00:04:07.310 --> 00:04:10.750 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: This one was
a cryogenics electric.

00:04:10.750 --> 00:04:14.185 align:middle line:84%
The fuels are 325 degrees
below zero, so it's a--

00:04:14.185 --> 00:04:15.060 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's cold.

00:04:15.060 --> 00:04:15.860 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:04:15.860 --> 00:04:17.490 align:middle line:90%
It's what we call a feely.

00:04:17.490 --> 00:04:19.459 align:middle line:84%
It's a liquid fuel
rocket engine.

00:04:19.459 --> 00:04:23.300 align:middle line:84%
And this one went
about 52,000 feet.

00:04:23.300 --> 00:04:24.320 align:middle line:90%
A little bit more than--

00:04:24.320 --> 00:04:26.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: 52,000 feet?

00:04:26.430 --> 00:04:27.230 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:04:27.230 --> 00:04:29.000 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did it come
down via parachute?

00:04:29.000 --> 00:04:29.330 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:04:29.330 --> 00:04:31.070 align:middle line:84%
I had radio guidance
on it, and I

00:04:31.070 --> 00:04:33.990 align:middle line:84%
had a little wire that trailed
out of as it was descending.

00:04:33.990 --> 00:04:35.250 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And you found it?

00:04:35.250 --> 00:04:37.220 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: It went right
back in the yard.

00:04:37.220 --> 00:04:38.219 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's amazing.

00:04:38.219 --> 00:04:41.590 align:middle line:90%
Well, how far did it drift away?

00:04:41.590 --> 00:04:42.850 align:middle line:90%
That's almost 10 miles high!

00:04:42.850 --> 00:04:43.650 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:04:43.650 --> 00:04:46.100 align:middle line:84%
Well, because of the upper
winds and the jet evaders

00:04:46.100 --> 00:04:49.010 align:middle line:84%
I had built inside
the stress vanes

00:04:49.010 --> 00:04:50.460 align:middle line:90%
allows me to steer things.

00:04:50.460 --> 00:04:52.830 align:middle line:90%
It's a steerable rocket.

00:04:52.830 --> 00:04:56.540 align:middle line:84%
And so I flew into
the wind on lift off.

00:04:56.540 --> 00:04:57.540 align:middle line:90%
It drifted back.

00:04:57.540 --> 00:05:02.160 align:middle line:84%
And by the way, I calculated
it on drift time to come back--

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:04.790 align:middle line:84%
see, it's in freefall for a
while, and then the ejection

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:06.560 align:middle line:90%
cycle and all that goes off.

00:05:06.560 --> 00:05:08.559 align:middle line:84%
But I got good
because I was lazy.

00:05:08.559 --> 00:05:10.100 align:middle line:84%
I didn't want to go
chase them, and I

00:05:10.100 --> 00:05:11.780 align:middle line:90%
didn't want to end up in trees.

00:05:11.780 --> 00:05:13.240 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did you have
little friends with you too

00:05:13.240 --> 00:05:13.910 align:middle line:90%
running around?

00:05:13.910 --> 00:05:14.951 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Actually, I did.

00:05:14.951 --> 00:05:17.510 align:middle line:84%
And that's the funny
part, because--

00:05:17.510 --> 00:05:20.780 align:middle line:84%
Iet's see, we were 10,
11, 12, those ages.

00:05:20.780 --> 00:05:24.500 align:middle line:90%
And this very first one was big.

00:05:24.500 --> 00:05:27.530 align:middle line:84%
And my mother saw my
friends down by the rocket.

00:05:27.530 --> 00:05:29.780 align:middle line:84%
And I were up about
100 yards away,

00:05:29.780 --> 00:05:31.340 align:middle line:84%
and I called
everybody yet to me.

00:05:31.340 --> 00:05:32.820 align:middle line:90%
I said, you can't stand there.

00:05:32.820 --> 00:05:35.067 align:middle line:84%
They're used Fourth of
July rockets, you know?

00:05:35.067 --> 00:05:36.650 align:middle line:84%
Light a fuse, stand
right next to it--

00:05:36.650 --> 00:05:37.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Little bottle rockets.

00:05:37.370 --> 00:05:38.210 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, and
watch it go up.

00:05:38.210 --> 00:05:40.140 align:middle line:84%
I said, you can't
stand down there, guys.

00:05:40.140 --> 00:05:40.580 align:middle line:90%
Why?

00:05:40.580 --> 00:05:41.920 align:middle line:90%
Well, you'll see in a minute.

00:05:41.920 --> 00:05:43.077 align:middle line:90%
So they came on up.

00:05:43.077 --> 00:05:43.910 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: [SWOOSHING]

00:05:43.910 --> 00:05:47.180 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Oh, I incinerated the
whole lower end of the yard.

00:05:47.180 --> 00:05:48.590 align:middle line:90%
It was just burnt to a crisp.

00:05:48.590 --> 00:05:51.170 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, at
age, David, did NASA

00:05:51.170 --> 00:05:56.102 align:middle line:84%
or other people start
noticing what you were doing?

00:05:56.102 --> 00:05:57.570 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: I was 13.

00:05:57.570 --> 00:05:58.217 align:middle line:90%


00:05:58.217 --> 00:05:59.050 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right away.

00:05:59.050 --> 00:05:59.610 align:middle line:90%
That day, huh?

00:05:59.610 --> 00:06:00.480 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, yeah.

00:06:00.480 --> 00:06:00.870 align:middle line:90%
They--

00:06:00.870 --> 00:06:02.411 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How did
they know about you?

00:06:02.411 --> 00:06:05.580 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, that was-- it
was an accident, actually.

00:06:05.580 --> 00:06:09.340 align:middle line:84%
I was trying to figure out
how some of these rockets

00:06:09.340 --> 00:06:13.000 align:middle line:84%
are malfunctioning, but I need
really high-speed cameras,

00:06:13.000 --> 00:06:13.800 align:middle line:90%
you know?

00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:16.180 align:middle line:90%
1,000 frames a second or faster.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:18.570 align:middle line:84%
And so I thought I'd
call the local news--

00:06:18.570 --> 00:06:20.065 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And borrow one, huh?

00:06:20.065 --> 00:06:20.450 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Exactly.

00:06:20.450 --> 00:06:21.683 align:middle line:90%
Yeah, I was a kid, you know?

00:06:21.683 --> 00:06:22.620 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You weren't
going to buy one.

00:06:22.620 --> 00:06:24.150 align:middle line:84%
You didn't have the
money for it then.

00:06:24.150 --> 00:06:24.980 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And they
got me on the phone,

00:06:24.980 --> 00:06:26.689 align:middle line:84%
and they said, how
fast do you need?

00:06:26.689 --> 00:06:28.730 align:middle line:84%
I said it's got to be over
1,000 frames a second.

00:06:28.730 --> 00:06:30.563 align:middle line:84%
They said, well, what
are you photographing?

00:06:30.563 --> 00:06:31.980 align:middle line:90%
I said, rockets.

00:06:31.980 --> 00:06:34.960 align:middle line:84%
And they were
quiet for a second.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:36.930 align:middle line:84%
Are you the person
launching rockets

00:06:36.930 --> 00:06:39.861 align:middle line:84%
we hear thundering in the
distance on a clear blue sky?

00:06:39.861 --> 00:06:41.235 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, what
city was this?

00:06:41.235 --> 00:06:41.940 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: This was Mt.

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:42.480 align:middle line:90%
Vernon.

00:06:42.480 --> 00:06:43.280 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:06:43.280 --> 00:06:45.240 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And so I
said, yeah, I think

00:06:45.240 --> 00:06:47.560 align:middle line:84%
that's my rockets
you're hearing.

00:06:47.560 --> 00:06:48.360 align:middle line:90%
Can you help me?

00:06:48.360 --> 00:06:51.540 align:middle line:84%
They said, you bet, and
they come flying out there

00:06:51.540 --> 00:06:52.440 align:middle line:90%
to see all this.

00:06:52.440 --> 00:06:54.210 align:middle line:90%
And their cameras helped.

00:06:54.210 --> 00:06:57.120 align:middle line:84%
But the very first one
I launched for them,

00:06:57.120 --> 00:06:59.336 align:middle line:90%
it came out of the pit.

00:06:59.336 --> 00:07:02.730 align:middle line:84%
And my dad was sitting
on the back of the car,

00:07:02.730 --> 00:07:05.740 align:middle line:84%
and he's smoking his pipe, and
the rocket comes ripping out

00:07:05.740 --> 00:07:07.812 align:middle line:90%
of there, and at such force.

00:07:07.812 --> 00:07:08.770 align:middle line:90%
I mean, these are mis--

00:07:08.770 --> 00:07:09.570 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And loud.

00:07:09.570 --> 00:07:12.148 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Oh, it's deafening.

00:07:12.148 --> 00:07:14.490 align:middle line:84%
And my dad said, David,
look at the photographers.

00:07:14.490 --> 00:07:15.290 align:middle line:90%
Turn around.

00:07:15.290 --> 00:07:16.706 align:middle line:84%
And both them are
staring straight

00:07:16.706 --> 00:07:17.887 align:middle line:90%
up watching the rocket--

00:07:17.887 --> 00:07:19.220 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: With their mouths open.

00:07:19.220 --> 00:07:21.120 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: --and the cameras are
hanging down by their side.

00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:21.740 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah,
instead of shooting--

00:07:21.740 --> 00:07:22.890 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They didn't
take a sing-- they

00:07:22.890 --> 00:07:23.920 align:middle line:90%
didn't get a single picture.

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:26.336 align:middle line:84%
So I told them I kind of thought
that was going to happen,

00:07:26.336 --> 00:07:28.790 align:middle line:84%
that's why I packed two
more, so let us reload.

00:07:28.790 --> 00:07:30.770 align:middle line:90%
And we got some great photos.

00:07:30.770 --> 00:07:34.610 align:middle line:84%
But that's when
they wrote a story

00:07:34.610 --> 00:07:35.900 align:middle line:90%
and it went on the front page.

00:07:35.900 --> 00:07:37.545 align:middle line:84%
And boy, after that,
everybody started

00:07:37.545 --> 00:07:38.670 align:middle line:90%
coming out of the woodwork.

00:07:38.670 --> 00:07:40.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So I would
assume by that time,

00:07:40.820 --> 00:07:43.160 align:middle line:84%
the media was doing
some stuff on you,

00:07:43.160 --> 00:07:47.514 align:middle line:84%
And the boys noticed, OK, who's
this 13-year-old kid, right?

00:07:47.514 --> 00:07:48.680 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Well, that's funny.

00:07:48.680 --> 00:07:51.830 align:middle line:84%
When we launched the
first one and my mother

00:07:51.830 --> 00:07:54.650 align:middle line:84%
was in the kitchen, and
everything in the kitchen

00:07:54.650 --> 00:07:55.670 align:middle line:90%
starts moving.

00:07:55.670 --> 00:07:58.097 align:middle line:84%
And that's called the
rockets going off.

00:07:58.097 --> 00:07:59.180 align:middle line:90%
And she comes running out.

00:07:59.180 --> 00:08:00.555 align:middle line:84%
And last time she
saw my friends,

00:08:00.555 --> 00:08:02.830 align:middle line:84%
they were down there
by the launchpad.

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:05.450 align:middle line:84%
And when I actually launched,
they were behind me.

00:08:05.450 --> 00:08:07.390 align:middle line:84%
And she said,
where's your friends?

00:08:07.390 --> 00:08:09.260 align:middle line:84%
And I turned around
to look at them,

00:08:09.260 --> 00:08:10.670 align:middle line:90%
they're gone like Bugs Bunny.

00:08:10.670 --> 00:08:11.470 align:middle line:90%
Just--

00:08:11.470 --> 00:08:11.820 align:middle line:90%
[WHISTLING]

00:08:11.820 --> 00:08:12.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:08:12.370 --> 00:08:14.420 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And they weren't even
allowed to play with matches,

00:08:14.420 --> 00:08:15.790 align:middle line:84%
and here I just
disintegrative a yard.

00:08:15.790 --> 00:08:17.910 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Yeah, you're blowing
up places and stuff like that.

00:08:17.910 --> 00:08:18.180 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:08:18.180 --> 00:08:20.560 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So that's let's jump
ahead for a second, David.

00:08:20.560 --> 00:08:22.405 align:middle line:84%
Let's jump ahead
to your involvement

00:08:22.405 --> 00:08:24.640 align:middle line:90%
in working with the military.

00:08:24.640 --> 00:08:26.260 align:middle line:90%
Area 51, especially.

00:08:26.260 --> 00:08:27.730 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: OK.

00:08:27.730 --> 00:08:32.770 align:middle line:10%
>> In 1989, a man called Bob
Lazar walked into a Las Vegas

00:08:32.770 --> 00:08:37.120 align:middle line:10%
TV station and gave a
remarkable interview.

00:08:37.120 --> 00:08:40.220 align:middle line:10%
He said that he'd worked
out in the Nevada desert

00:08:40.220 --> 00:08:45.150 align:middle line:10%
at a top-secret facility
known as Area 51.

00:08:45.150 --> 00:08:48.820 align:middle line:10%
He said he worked on a
highly classified project,

00:08:48.820 --> 00:08:53.277 align:middle line:10%
reverse engineering
recovered alien spacecraft.

00:08:53.277 --> 00:08:56.410 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:08:56.410 --> 00:08:59.420 align:middle line:10%
His story was a
worldwide sensation,

00:08:59.420 --> 00:09:05.170 align:middle line:10%
and Area 51 became a household
name, synonymous with UFOs,

00:09:05.170 --> 00:09:10.240 align:middle line:10%
secret projects, and
little green men.

00:09:10.240 --> 00:09:13.800 align:middle line:10%
And yet, neither the US
government nor its military

00:09:13.800 --> 00:09:16.280 align:middle line:10%
have ever denied his claims.

00:09:16.280 --> 00:09:18.450 align:middle line:10%
And they still don't
officially confirm

00:09:18.450 --> 00:09:22.770 align:middle line:10%
that Area 51 exists,
despite satellite photos

00:09:22.770 --> 00:09:23.730 align:middle line:10%
proving it does.

00:09:23.730 --> 00:09:26.450 align:middle line:10%


00:09:26.450 --> 00:09:29.582 align:middle line:10%
Many dismiss Bob
Lazar as a fantasist.

00:09:29.582 --> 00:09:32.840 align:middle line:10%
And yet others see him
as a whistleblower,

00:09:32.840 --> 00:09:38.320 align:middle line:10%
exposing a government cover-up
of UFOs and alien contact.

00:09:38.320 --> 00:09:43.726 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:09:43.726 --> 00:09:45.850 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: David Adair,
that story, of course,

00:09:45.850 --> 00:09:48.490 align:middle line:84%
was broken by our colleague
and friend, George Knapp, when

00:09:48.490 --> 00:09:51.820 align:middle line:84%
Bob Lazar walked into
his television station.

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:54.910 align:middle line:90%
What do you think of Area 51?

00:09:54.910 --> 00:09:57.250 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: It's still
a mystery to me.

00:09:57.250 --> 00:10:01.300 align:middle line:84%
My exposure was this very
contained in one day,

00:10:01.300 --> 00:10:04.190 align:middle line:84%
but I saw enough
in one day to know

00:10:04.190 --> 00:10:07.810 align:middle line:84%
that this has been an
ongoing operation with plans

00:10:07.810 --> 00:10:10.330 align:middle line:90%
of expansion everywhere.

00:10:10.330 --> 00:10:14.230 align:middle line:84%
When we come into
land, the runaways

00:10:14.230 --> 00:10:17.860 align:middle line:84%
were marked out with flags,
and chalk lines, and all that.

00:10:17.860 --> 00:10:23.081 align:middle line:84%
What we landed on would later
be a taxiway interconnecting.

00:10:23.081 --> 00:10:24.580 align:middle line:84%
But you could tell
they were getting

00:10:24.580 --> 00:10:25.960 align:middle line:90%
ready to build a lot of--

00:10:25.960 --> 00:10:28.970 align:middle line:84%
it was 1971 when I was there,
and they really getting

00:10:28.970 --> 00:10:30.520 align:middle line:90%
expanded like crazy.

00:10:30.520 --> 00:10:32.920 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Had the story
about UFOs and things

00:10:32.920 --> 00:10:34.720 align:middle line:90%
really popped by that time?

00:10:34.720 --> 00:10:36.540 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Not much.

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:40.094 align:middle line:84%
And I never heard the
term "Area 51" not until--

00:10:40.094 --> 00:10:41.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Hardly anybody did.

00:10:41.260 --> 00:10:42.060 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:10:42.060 --> 00:10:44.485 align:middle line:84%
The only thing I knew
it by was Groom Lake,

00:10:44.485 --> 00:10:46.690 align:middle line:90%
and it was a dry lake bed.

00:10:46.690 --> 00:10:50.689 align:middle line:84%
And I even had an argument
with Arthur Rudolph over that.

00:10:50.689 --> 00:10:52.480 align:middle line:84%
I said, why are we
going to a dry lake bed?

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:53.780 align:middle line:90%
Look at the jet you're on.

00:10:53.780 --> 00:10:54.820 align:middle line:90%
It's got rubber tires.

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:57.430 align:middle line:84%
You're going to plow
up dirt to its belly.

00:10:57.430 --> 00:11:00.820 align:middle line:84%
And he told me to just shut
up and get on the plane.

00:11:00.820 --> 00:11:03.250 align:middle line:84%
And when we get there,
there's a big base there.

00:11:03.250 --> 00:11:05.120 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: What did they
want you there for?

00:11:05.120 --> 00:11:06.620 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, they
brought me there

00:11:06.620 --> 00:11:09.820 align:middle line:84%
to see a piece of hardware
they were working on,

00:11:09.820 --> 00:11:12.820 align:middle line:84%
and it was an electromagnetic
fusion containment engine.

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:14.260 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Was made by us?

00:11:14.260 --> 00:11:15.130 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:11:15.130 --> 00:11:17.664 align:middle line:84%
And I know it wasn't,
because I'd just

00:11:17.664 --> 00:11:18.955 align:middle line:90%
got through building my my own.

00:11:18.955 --> 00:11:20.050 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Somebody else, right?

00:11:20.050 --> 00:11:21.133 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, it's from--

00:11:21.133 --> 00:11:23.890 align:middle line:84%
it was not from our
technological base.

00:11:23.890 --> 00:11:25.200 align:middle line:90%
It wasn't ours.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:27.370 align:middle line:84%
It wasn't theirs,
meaning the Soviets.

00:11:27.370 --> 00:11:29.800 align:middle line:84%
It was from some--
it was off-world.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:33.490 align:middle line:84%
And the most telltale
thing about it

00:11:33.490 --> 00:11:35.350 align:middle line:90%
was the way it was constructed.

00:11:35.350 --> 00:11:38.080 align:middle line:84%
Mine was about 3
and 1/2 feet long,

00:11:38.080 --> 00:11:40.090 align:middle line:90%
about 18 inches in diameter.

00:11:40.090 --> 00:11:42.550 align:middle line:84%
But this thing, when they
pulled the curtain up on it,

00:11:42.550 --> 00:11:46.990 align:middle line:84%
it's sitting on the stage, it's
the same size of an 18-wheeler.

00:11:46.990 --> 00:11:47.800 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Gees.

00:11:47.800 --> 00:11:51.910 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: It's 75 feet long, 22
feet wide, and 15 feet tall.

00:11:51.910 --> 00:11:54.430 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did they tell
you how they obtained it?

00:11:54.430 --> 00:11:55.470 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: I asked them.

00:11:55.470 --> 00:11:57.800 align:middle line:90%
And this is 1971.

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:58.600 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:11:58.600 --> 00:12:01.060 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They're very
condescending to a 17-year-old.

00:12:01.060 --> 00:12:03.190 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: 14 years
before that was Roswell.

00:12:03.190 --> 00:12:04.180 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Exactly.

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:08.110 align:middle line:84%
And I said, where did
you guys get this?

00:12:08.110 --> 00:12:11.050 align:middle line:84%
You want me to help you with
it, it's got a big damaged area,

00:12:11.050 --> 00:12:12.530 align:middle line:90%
and it's not running.

00:12:12.530 --> 00:12:15.110 align:middle line:84%
They said, well, we're
working on it, but--

00:12:15.110 --> 00:12:16.810 align:middle line:84%
Well, where's the
people working on it?

00:12:16.810 --> 00:12:18.520 align:middle line:84%
Oh, well, they're
on summer vacation,

00:12:18.520 --> 00:12:20.181 align:middle line:90%
like you get summer vacation.

00:12:20.181 --> 00:12:21.430 align:middle line:90%
Well, did you leave any notes?

00:12:21.430 --> 00:12:21.990 align:middle line:90%
Can I read?

00:12:21.990 --> 00:12:24.520 align:middle line:84%
And he goes, well, they have
homework like you do, son.

00:12:24.520 --> 00:12:26.540 align:middle line:84%
They take their
homework with them.

00:12:26.540 --> 00:12:28.250 align:middle line:84%
And I knew right then they're
lying through their teeth.

00:12:28.250 --> 00:12:29.140 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah, absolutely.

00:12:29.140 --> 00:12:30.040 align:middle line:90%
What was your job?

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:31.780 align:middle line:90%
What did they want you to do?

00:12:31.780 --> 00:12:35.650 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They wanted me to show
them how the first ignition

00:12:35.650 --> 00:12:37.590 align:middle line:90%
process occurred--

00:12:37.590 --> 00:12:39.230 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Of this
piece of machinery?

00:12:39.230 --> 00:12:40.100 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, and--

00:12:40.100 --> 00:12:41.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Did you know?

00:12:41.610 --> 00:12:43.910 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I had a better
handle on it than they did,

00:12:43.910 --> 00:12:45.701 align:middle line:84%
cause I'd just gotten
through building one,

00:12:45.701 --> 00:12:48.370 align:middle line:90%
although mine was small.

00:12:48.370 --> 00:12:51.415 align:middle line:84%
But it's like if you're building
an internal combustion engine

00:12:51.415 --> 00:12:52.780 align:middle line:90%
and you have a Model A engine.

00:12:52.780 --> 00:12:54.130 align:middle line:90%
That's what mine was.

00:12:54.130 --> 00:12:58.070 align:middle line:84%
And then you have a big
Lamborghini engine next to it.

00:12:58.070 --> 00:13:00.220 align:middle line:84%
One is way more sophisticated
and more powerful--

00:13:00.220 --> 00:13:00.370 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Night and day.

00:13:00.370 --> 00:13:02.590 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: --but they both
still are internal combustion

00:13:02.590 --> 00:13:02.830 align:middle line:90%
engines.

00:13:02.830 --> 00:13:03.400 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Right.

00:13:03.400 --> 00:13:05.410 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: So mine is an
electromagnetic fusion

00:13:05.410 --> 00:13:07.410 align:middle line:84%
containment device,
and so was theirs.

00:13:07.410 --> 00:13:09.430 align:middle line:84%
But theirs was so
much more powerful.

00:13:09.430 --> 00:13:11.129 align:middle line:90%
And I was just--

00:13:11.129 --> 00:13:12.670 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, when
you say "theirs",

00:13:12.670 --> 00:13:14.350 align:middle line:90%
it really wasn't theirs, right?

00:13:14.350 --> 00:13:14.530 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:13:14.530 --> 00:13:15.860 align:middle line:90%
Well, wherever it came from.

00:13:15.860 --> 00:13:16.290 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Wherever it came from.

00:13:16.290 --> 00:13:17.373 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: And I asked them.

00:13:17.373 --> 00:13:21.720 align:middle line:84%
I said-- at the end,
after I got to inspect it,

00:13:21.720 --> 00:13:22.880 align:middle line:90%
we got into an argument.

00:13:22.880 --> 00:13:24.760 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I
started asking things.

00:13:24.760 --> 00:13:30.100 align:middle line:84%
And I said, this is not from
the neighborhood, is it, boys?

00:13:30.100 --> 00:13:32.320 align:middle line:84%
And seeing a
17-year-old, they didn't

00:13:32.320 --> 00:13:35.620 align:middle line:84%
think I'd be putting it
together so quick in my head.

00:13:35.620 --> 00:13:40.090 align:middle line:84%
And I said this thing
is a power plant.

00:13:40.090 --> 00:13:43.150 align:middle line:84%
It's not-- it's more than an
engine, it's a power plant,

00:13:43.150 --> 00:13:45.057 align:middle line:90%
and it came out of a vehicle.

00:13:45.057 --> 00:13:45.890 align:middle line:90%
Where's the vehicle?

00:13:45.890 --> 00:13:46.300 align:middle line:90%


00:13:46.300 --> 00:13:46.510 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:13:46.510 --> 00:13:47.940 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And in
proportion to size--

00:13:47.940 --> 00:13:49.273 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: You were getting close.

00:13:49.273 --> 00:13:51.670 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, and
the proportional size,

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:55.094 align:middle line:84%
that ship would have to be
bigger than a football field.

00:13:55.094 --> 00:13:57.010 align:middle line:84%
And I said, there's a
crew that comes with it.

00:13:57.010 --> 00:13:58.660 align:middle line:84%
What did you do
with them people?

00:13:58.660 --> 00:13:59.460 align:middle line:90%
And--

00:13:59.460 --> 00:14:02.126 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: You were asking way too
many questions for them, right?

00:14:02.126 --> 00:14:04.040 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I was--
yeah, I got in trouble

00:14:04.040 --> 00:14:06.310 align:middle line:90%
the second we went down there.

00:14:06.310 --> 00:14:09.110 align:middle line:84%
And you could see this
cavernous underground.

00:14:09.110 --> 00:14:11.410 align:middle line:84%
It stretched so far that
it bent with the curvature

00:14:11.410 --> 00:14:12.370 align:middle line:90%
of the Earth.

00:14:12.370 --> 00:14:13.170 align:middle line:90%
That's how big--

00:14:13.170 --> 00:14:13.430 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:14:13.430 --> 00:14:14.830 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: You couldn't
see the end of it.

00:14:14.830 --> 00:14:16.540 align:middle line:84%
And my first question
out of my mouth

00:14:16.540 --> 00:14:18.640 align:middle line:84%
was, what did you guys
do with all the dirt?

00:14:18.640 --> 00:14:21.390 align:middle line:84%
And they got so
angry about that.

00:14:21.390 --> 00:14:22.920 align:middle line:84%
And I thought,
well, why would you

00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:24.660 align:middle line:90%
get angry about asking what--

00:14:24.660 --> 00:14:27.340 align:middle line:84%
you guys are packing some
kind of technology down here.

00:14:27.340 --> 00:14:29.655 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Didn't they expect
you to ask these questions?

00:14:29.655 --> 00:14:30.425 align:middle line:90%
My gosh.

00:14:30.425 --> 00:14:31.925 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They
thought-- well, you've

00:14:31.925 --> 00:14:33.750 align:middle line:84%
got to remember our
society structure.

00:14:33.750 --> 00:14:38.150 align:middle line:84%
In 1971, teenagers just
didn't get any respect.

00:14:38.150 --> 00:14:41.054 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, teenagers
weren't called down to Area 51

00:14:41.054 --> 00:14:42.470 align:middle line:84%
to analyze some
UFO engine, right?

00:14:42.470 --> 00:14:42.575 align:middle line:90%


00:14:42.575 --> 00:14:43.700 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Well, that's true.

00:14:43.700 --> 00:14:46.500 align:middle line:84%
Well, they didn't-- well,
you know what it was?

00:14:46.500 --> 00:14:47.880 align:middle line:90%
They were in a hurry.

00:14:47.880 --> 00:14:49.380 align:middle line:90%
They had a problem.

00:14:49.380 --> 00:14:52.430 align:middle line:84%
They were racing to something
called First Strike,

00:14:52.430 --> 00:14:54.540 align:middle line:84%
and I'd never heard
of that before.

00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:56.679 align:middle line:84%
And I thought, is this
some kind of baseball game?

00:14:56.679 --> 00:14:57.970 align:middle line:90%
And then as they kept talking--

00:14:57.970 --> 00:14:59.070 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: I wish it were.

00:14:59.070 --> 00:14:59.870 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:14:59.870 --> 00:15:02.790 align:middle line:84%
Then when they-- yeah, after I
heard him use the term "MAD",

00:15:02.790 --> 00:15:05.240 align:middle line:84%
I knew what that was,
Mutual Assured Destruction.

00:15:05.240 --> 00:15:05.650 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's right.

00:15:05.650 --> 00:15:05.690 align:middle line:90%


00:15:05.690 --> 00:15:08.640 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And I went, oh god,
they're trying to win MAD.

00:15:08.640 --> 00:15:11.570 align:middle line:84%
The only way to win MAD
would be first strike.

00:15:11.570 --> 00:15:14.940 align:middle line:84%
And I went, oh man, I just gave
them an operating prototype

00:15:14.940 --> 00:15:17.570 align:middle line:84%
up on a desert floor
that just landed there,

00:15:17.570 --> 00:15:22.350 align:middle line:84%
and my engine, my
rocket, is not designed

00:15:22.350 --> 00:15:26.340 align:middle line:84%
for a launch in this atmosphere,
in this gravity field.

00:15:26.340 --> 00:15:29.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Were they able, David,
to ever duplicate that engine?

00:15:29.400 --> 00:15:29.620 align:middle line:90%


00:15:29.620 --> 00:15:29.885 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:15:29.885 --> 00:15:31.510 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: They were
never able to do it.

00:15:31.510 --> 00:15:33.280 align:middle line:84%
And where do you
think it is today?

00:15:33.280 --> 00:15:34.080 align:middle line:90%
Still there?

00:15:34.080 --> 00:15:34.790 align:middle line:90%


00:15:34.790 --> 00:15:36.260 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: I think
it's still there,

00:15:36.260 --> 00:15:38.570 align:middle line:84%
because you just can't move
something around like that

00:15:38.570 --> 00:15:39.569 align:middle line:90%
without people noticing.

00:15:39.569 --> 00:15:41.820 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: How big do
you estimate the craft

00:15:41.820 --> 00:15:44.110 align:middle line:84%
to be that that piece
of machinery was in?

00:15:44.110 --> 00:15:44.910 align:middle line:90%


00:15:44.910 --> 00:15:46.710 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Bigger than
a football field.

00:15:46.710 --> 00:15:48.960 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, and we
do get reports of that.

00:15:48.960 --> 00:15:49.048 align:middle line:90%


00:15:49.048 --> 00:15:50.131 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: That's something.

00:15:50.131 --> 00:15:51.870 align:middle line:84%
Yeah, whenever I
hear triangle reports

00:15:51.870 --> 00:15:54.810 align:middle line:84%
of what they call
"motherships" and stuff,

00:15:54.810 --> 00:15:56.280 align:middle line:90%
yeah, I think I saw one of them.

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:59.070 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did it look like
it was made with technology

00:15:59.070 --> 00:16:00.000 align:middle line:90%
that we possessed?

00:16:00.000 --> 00:16:00.210 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:16:00.210 --> 00:16:01.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: I mean, were
there bolts in there

00:16:01.500 --> 00:16:01.950 align:middle line:90%
and stuff like that?

00:16:01.950 --> 00:16:02.040 align:middle line:90%


00:16:02.040 --> 00:16:02.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:05.720 align:middle line:84%
That's what-- that
was the telltale sign.

00:16:05.720 --> 00:16:10.050 align:middle line:84%
On mine, I had miles of the
wiring, nuts and bolts--

00:16:10.050 --> 00:16:10.850 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Exactly.

00:16:10.850 --> 00:16:10.973 align:middle line:90%


00:16:10.973 --> 00:16:12.210 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: --weld
lines, seal lines.

00:16:12.210 --> 00:16:13.360 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Solder
points, everything.

00:16:13.360 --> 00:16:14.640 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Exactly, all this.

00:16:14.640 --> 00:16:18.810 align:middle line:84%
And on this thing, as big
as it was, not one wire.

00:16:18.810 --> 00:16:20.460 align:middle line:90%
Not one bolt. Not one nut.

00:16:20.460 --> 00:16:21.720 align:middle line:90%
Not one weld line.

00:16:21.720 --> 00:16:23.370 align:middle line:90%
Not a seam anywhere.

00:16:23.370 --> 00:16:25.680 align:middle line:84%
It looked like an
eggplant that just grew.

00:16:25.680 --> 00:16:29.070 align:middle line:84%
And that's when I started
realizing, this thing is more--

00:16:29.070 --> 00:16:30.810 align:middle line:90%
it's not a machine.

00:16:30.810 --> 00:16:33.810 align:middle line:84%
It looks like it's organic,
but yet it is a machine.

00:16:33.810 --> 00:16:34.610 align:middle line:90%
It's both.

00:16:34.610 --> 00:16:37.710 align:middle line:84%
It's inorganic and
organic at the same time.

00:16:37.710 --> 00:16:38.520 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Amazing.

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:40.650 align:middle line:84%
You have been a
champion for fighting

00:16:40.650 --> 00:16:42.210 align:middle line:90%
to protect our power grid.

00:16:42.210 --> 00:16:44.080 align:middle line:84%
You've been doing
this for years.

00:16:44.080 --> 00:16:46.530 align:middle line:84%
We're going to talk about
the various things you've

00:16:46.530 --> 00:16:49.500 align:middle line:84%
been doing to try to
get that grid protected.

00:16:49.500 --> 00:16:50.880 align:middle line:84%
But there are a
couple of sources

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:52.740 align:middle line:84%
that could knock the
grid down, and that

00:16:52.740 --> 00:16:56.880 align:middle line:84%
would be either a solar
flare or CME from the sun,

00:16:56.880 --> 00:16:59.790 align:middle line:84%
or an EMP attack,
a nuke, detonated

00:16:59.790 --> 00:17:02.430 align:middle line:84%
in the atmosphere that would
sprinkle down and wipe out

00:17:02.430 --> 00:17:03.540 align:middle line:90%
the power grid as well.

00:17:03.540 --> 00:17:04.340 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Right.

00:17:04.340 --> 00:17:06.660 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Tell us about
solar flares, first of all.

00:17:06.660 --> 00:17:10.720 align:middle line:84%
And we have avoided and dodged
some of them in the past.

00:17:10.720 --> 00:17:11.520 align:middle line:90%
We've been lucky.

00:17:11.520 --> 00:17:12.320 align:middle line:90%


00:17:12.320 --> 00:17:15.089 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Just-- we've
been incredibly lucky.

00:17:15.089 --> 00:17:18.780 align:middle line:84%
We should go to a lottery,
because you'll probably win,

00:17:18.780 --> 00:17:20.819 align:middle line:90%
you've been so lucky.

00:17:20.819 --> 00:17:24.250 align:middle line:84%
The thing with the CMEs,
the Coronal Mass Ejection--

00:17:24.250 --> 00:17:28.380 align:middle line:84%
think of on a hot day, you take
your hand against your forehead

00:17:28.380 --> 00:17:30.980 align:middle line:84%
and you wipe the sweat off,
and sling it off your hand,

00:17:30.980 --> 00:17:32.580 align:middle line:84%
and you see the
little beads of sweat.

00:17:32.580 --> 00:17:33.060 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:17:33.060 --> 00:17:33.135 align:middle line:90%


00:17:33.135 --> 00:17:34.650 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Well, that's
exactly what the sun's doing.

00:17:34.650 --> 00:17:36.344 align:middle line:84%
It's throwing off
beads of sweat,

00:17:36.344 --> 00:17:38.010 align:middle line:84%
but these beads are
a little bit bigger.

00:17:38.010 --> 00:17:38.550 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh yeah.

00:17:38.550 --> 00:17:38.700 align:middle line:90%


00:17:38.700 --> 00:17:40.830 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They are this
size and mass of Mt.

00:17:40.830 --> 00:17:41.970 align:middle line:90%
Everest.

00:17:41.970 --> 00:17:45.810 align:middle line:84%
They are highly-charged
plasma ball,

00:17:45.810 --> 00:17:49.950 align:middle line:84%
and it's moving at
just below light speed.

00:17:49.950 --> 00:17:52.655 align:middle line:84%
It will cover 93 million
miles in eight hours.

00:17:52.655 --> 00:17:54.780 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's how long
it would take to get here?

00:17:54.780 --> 00:17:55.030 align:middle line:90%


00:17:55.030 --> 00:17:56.850 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Right, 8 to 12
hours, depending on orbit.

00:17:56.850 --> 00:17:58.370 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It doesn't
kill people directly--

00:17:58.370 --> 00:17:58.505 align:middle line:90%


00:17:58.505 --> 00:17:58.640 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:17:58.640 --> 00:17:59.870 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --but it
takes out the grid.

00:17:59.870 --> 00:18:00.670 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Right.

00:18:00.670 --> 00:18:02.492 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The electrical
systems, computers.

00:18:02.492 --> 00:18:03.180 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR:

00:18:03.180 --> 00:18:04.410 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Anything
that's powered up.

00:18:04.410 --> 00:18:05.210 align:middle line:90%


00:18:05.210 --> 00:18:07.851 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: We were hit by one in
September 1869, called the--

00:18:07.851 --> 00:18:09.100 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: The Carrington Event.

00:18:09.100 --> 00:18:09.255 align:middle line:90%


00:18:09.255 --> 00:18:10.740 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: The Carrington Event.

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:12.289 align:middle line:90%
And it did tear up the--

00:18:12.289 --> 00:18:13.830 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The telegraph
system, right?

00:18:13.830 --> 00:18:13.905 align:middle line:90%


00:18:13.905 --> 00:18:15.571 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, but
also something else--

00:18:15.571 --> 00:18:18.061 align:middle line:84%
the Trans-Atlantic Ocean
Cable, knocked it out.

00:18:18.061 --> 00:18:19.060 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That got fried.

00:18:19.060 --> 00:18:22.770 align:middle line:84%
And I was also told
that the railroad--

00:18:22.770 --> 00:18:27.090 align:middle line:84%
metal ties on the
railroad got fried,

00:18:27.090 --> 00:18:29.430 align:middle line:84%
and people could see
them actually crackling.

00:18:29.430 --> 00:18:29.514 align:middle line:90%


00:18:29.514 --> 00:18:31.680 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, it was a--
well, it would make sense.

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:33.520 align:middle line:90%
That's a terrific ground an--

00:18:33.520 --> 00:18:34.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: It's like an antenna.

00:18:34.770 --> 00:18:34.920 align:middle line:90%


00:18:34.920 --> 00:18:36.390 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, exactly, which--

00:18:36.390 --> 00:18:39.510 align:middle line:90%


00:18:39.510 --> 00:18:43.920 align:middle line:84%
there's something about
that concerning UFOs.

00:18:43.920 --> 00:18:48.400 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Well, we can't contain
the solar flare from the sun.

00:18:48.400 --> 00:18:52.230 align:middle line:84%
If we are directly
in-line with the sun,

00:18:52.230 --> 00:18:56.430 align:middle line:84%
and an X flare, which is a big
one, comes out of that sun,

00:18:56.430 --> 00:18:57.450 align:middle line:90%
it's going to hit us.

00:18:57.450 --> 00:18:57.550 align:middle line:90%


00:18:57.550 --> 00:18:58.460 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Oh, it will.

00:18:58.460 --> 00:19:01.110 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And you're
saying within 8 hours

00:19:01.110 --> 00:19:02.160 align:middle line:90%
it starts to affect me?

00:19:02.160 --> 00:19:05.935 align:middle line:84%
What about satellites that are
up there, and they get hit too?

00:19:05.935 --> 00:19:06.735 align:middle line:90%


00:19:06.735 --> 00:19:09.600 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: They're
toast, unless they're

00:19:09.600 --> 00:19:12.570 align:middle line:84%
Echo A and B.
Those are satellite

00:19:12.570 --> 00:19:15.150 align:middle line:90%
designed to be hit by CMEs.

00:19:15.150 --> 00:19:20.940 align:middle line:84%
And on July 23, 2012, type that
computer and read up on that,

00:19:20.940 --> 00:19:24.270 align:middle line:90%
we almost died that day.

00:19:24.270 --> 00:19:25.640 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Nobody knew it, right?

00:19:25.640 --> 00:19:25.695 align:middle line:90%


00:19:25.695 --> 00:19:27.736 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yep, and they
didn't say a word about it

00:19:27.736 --> 00:19:28.620 align:middle line:90%
for two years.

00:19:28.620 --> 00:19:31.530 align:middle line:84%
The story was not released
by media or the government

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:33.630 align:middle line:90%
till two years later.

00:19:33.630 --> 00:19:36.480 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: There is a
difference between CMEs,

00:19:36.480 --> 00:19:38.945 align:middle line:84%
Coronal Mass Ejections,
and solar flares, right?

00:19:38.945 --> 00:19:39.100 align:middle line:90%


00:19:39.100 --> 00:19:39.900 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yes.

00:19:39.900 --> 00:19:41.678 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Let's take a look.

00:19:41.678 --> 00:19:49.662 align:middle line:10%
[MUSIC PLAYING]

00:19:49.662 --> 00:21:15.590 align:middle line:90%


00:21:15.590 --> 00:21:18.320 align:middle line:84%
David, that video was
provided to us by NASA.

00:21:18.320 --> 00:21:22.550 align:middle line:84%
And considering the technology
we have on this planet today,

00:21:22.550 --> 00:21:25.250 align:middle line:84%
we've been pretty darn
lucky that we really

00:21:25.250 --> 00:21:26.210 align:middle line:90%
haven't been zapped.

00:21:26.210 --> 00:21:26.795 align:middle line:90%


00:21:26.795 --> 00:21:27.595 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:21:27.595 --> 00:21:30.200 align:middle line:90%
On July 23, we should have died.

00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:33.445 align:middle line:84%
If we had been just out of
place by just a fraction of a--

00:21:33.445 --> 00:21:35.945 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Because it went out
the side of the sun, didn't it?

00:21:35.945 --> 00:21:36.012 align:middle line:90%


00:21:36.012 --> 00:21:38.012 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, well there
were not one, not two,

00:21:38.012 --> 00:21:39.360 align:middle line:90%
but three CME balls.

00:21:39.360 --> 00:21:43.130 align:middle line:84%
The size of each one of
them, the size of Carrington,

00:21:43.130 --> 00:21:48.290 align:middle line:84%
came at us on July 23, 2012,
crossed 93 million miles

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:51.140 align:middle line:84%
in 8 and 1/2 hours,
and passed so

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:54.010 align:middle line:84%
close they passed
between us and the moon.

00:21:54.010 --> 00:21:56.270 align:middle line:84%
They were only
110,000 miles away.

00:21:56.270 --> 00:21:58.645 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Just a little bit
more and we would've been hit.

00:21:58.645 --> 00:21:59.444 align:middle line:90%


00:21:59.444 --> 00:22:01.460 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: If they showed
up one day earlier,

00:22:01.460 --> 00:22:02.780 align:middle line:90%
we'd have been hit dead-center.

00:22:02.780 --> 00:22:04.460 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: The alignment
was right then, wasn't it?

00:22:04.460 --> 00:22:04.670 align:middle line:90%


00:22:04.670 --> 00:22:05.989 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah, and it--

00:22:05.989 --> 00:22:07.530 align:middle line:84%
those three hitting
us, the first one

00:22:07.530 --> 00:22:12.000 align:middle line:84%
would have stripped away the
Van Allen radiation belts.

00:22:12.000 --> 00:22:15.890 align:middle line:84%
Then the other two would
have come in and cascaded

00:22:15.890 --> 00:22:21.020 align:middle line:84%
over the surface of the Earth,
and everything would have went.

00:22:21.020 --> 00:22:23.060 align:middle line:90%
That much power coming in--

00:22:23.060 --> 00:22:25.280 align:middle line:84%
a normal power line
in your neighborhood

00:22:25.280 --> 00:22:26.410 align:middle line:90%
cares about 5,500 volts.

00:22:26.410 --> 00:22:27.210 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: OK.

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:28.010 align:middle line:90%


00:22:28.010 --> 00:22:30.860 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: These things would
drop 3.2 million volts

00:22:30.860 --> 00:22:31.940 align:middle line:90%
into the lines.

00:22:31.940 --> 00:22:32.225 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Fried.

00:22:32.225 --> 00:22:33.215 align:middle line:90%
They'd all be fried.

00:22:33.215 --> 00:22:34.630 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: It's worse than fried.

00:22:34.630 --> 00:22:37.100 align:middle line:84%
They'll turn red,
then white, and then--

00:22:37.100 --> 00:22:38.150 align:middle line:90%
they're gone.

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:41.480 align:middle line:84%
But before they go, that
gray canisters on the poles,

00:22:41.480 --> 00:22:44.420 align:middle line:84%
the transformers,
they're filled with oil,

00:22:44.420 --> 00:22:48.140 align:middle line:84%
and they use the oil
to dissipate the heat.

00:22:48.140 --> 00:22:50.970 align:middle line:84%
But with that much surge coming
in, that oil turns into napalm.

00:22:50.970 --> 00:22:51.770 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Oh, Gees.

00:22:51.770 --> 00:22:51.875 align:middle line:90%


00:22:51.875 --> 00:22:53.870 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: So imagine
every transformer

00:22:53.870 --> 00:22:56.650 align:middle line:84%
in the United States all
exploding simultaneously.

00:22:56.650 --> 00:22:58.610 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Did we get
any warning at all

00:22:58.610 --> 00:23:00.270 align:middle line:90%
beyond the six to eight hours?

00:23:00.270 --> 00:23:00.750 align:middle line:90%


00:23:00.750 --> 00:23:01.550 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:23:01.550 --> 00:23:02.090 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We don't?

00:23:02.090 --> 00:23:02.225 align:middle line:90%


00:23:02.225 --> 00:23:03.025 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:23:03.025 --> 00:23:06.500 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: So we can't tell
right now that a coronal mass

00:23:06.500 --> 00:23:10.880 align:middle line:84%
ejection is brewing on the
sun, and is about to spout?

00:23:10.880 --> 00:23:11.680 align:middle line:90%
It has to happen?

00:23:11.680 --> 00:23:11.995 align:middle line:90%


00:23:11.995 --> 00:23:14.990 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: It has to happen, and
then you can start tracking it.

00:23:14.990 --> 00:23:19.830 align:middle line:84%
Then the satellites Echo
1 and 2, or A and B,

00:23:19.830 --> 00:23:23.430 align:middle line:84%
will start giving an idea
of trajectories and such.

00:23:23.430 --> 00:23:25.450 align:middle line:84%
They even have a-- you'd
have enough heads-up

00:23:25.450 --> 00:23:28.670 align:middle line:84%
to do a few things,
but not much.

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:31.230 align:middle line:84%
It's just whenever mother
nature feels like it.

00:23:31.230 --> 00:23:34.470 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's not a matter of
if, it's just a matter of when,

00:23:34.470 --> 00:23:35.270 align:middle line:90%
isn't it?

00:23:35.270 --> 00:23:36.070 align:middle line:90%


00:23:36.070 --> 00:23:38.940 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Absolutely,
And we're way overdue.

00:23:38.940 --> 00:23:41.540 align:middle line:84%
We've got another
Carrington Event coming,

00:23:41.540 --> 00:23:43.230 align:middle line:84%
and I don't know
why we didn't get--

00:23:43.230 --> 00:23:45.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Does the
planet get hit, or maybe

00:23:45.260 --> 00:23:46.475 align:middle line:90%
that portion of the planet?

00:23:46.475 --> 00:23:46.970 align:middle line:90%


00:23:46.970 --> 00:23:47.150 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: No.

00:23:47.150 --> 00:23:47.800 align:middle line:90%
When it comes in--

00:23:47.800 --> 00:23:49.890 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Let's say India was
facing the sun at that point.

00:23:49.890 --> 00:23:49.951 align:middle line:90%


00:23:49.951 --> 00:23:50.950 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Doesn't matter.

00:23:50.950 --> 00:23:55.220 align:middle line:84%
It'll come in, it'll strike
the Van Allen radiation belts.

00:23:55.220 --> 00:23:58.260 align:middle line:84%
Normally, the balls
split in half.

00:23:58.260 --> 00:24:00.686 align:middle line:84%
They come around to the
back side, they collide,

00:24:00.686 --> 00:24:02.810 align:middle line:84%
then they come down through
the Earth's atmosphere.

00:24:02.810 --> 00:24:04.530 align:middle line:84%
They'll come through
the ionosphere,

00:24:04.530 --> 00:24:06.440 align:middle line:90%
the stratosphere, mesosphere.

00:24:06.440 --> 00:24:07.940 align:middle line:84%
Once they get to
the troposphere,

00:24:07.940 --> 00:24:10.259 align:middle line:84%
they're starting to cascade
all over the planet.

00:24:10.259 --> 00:24:12.050 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: And it stays
that way for a while?

00:24:12.050 --> 00:24:12.235 align:middle line:90%


00:24:12.235 --> 00:24:13.430 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:24:13.430 --> 00:24:16.040 align:middle line:84%
When the Carrington
Event happened,

00:24:16.040 --> 00:24:20.000 align:middle line:84%
that night in New York
City, the Aurora Borealis

00:24:20.000 --> 00:24:22.520 align:middle line:84%
was charred so hot that it went
all the way to the Equator.

00:24:22.520 --> 00:24:25.207 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: That's that light glow
people see in the sky, right?

00:24:25.207 --> 00:24:25.637 align:middle line:90%


00:24:25.637 --> 00:24:27.470 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: Exactly, the
green Northern Lights.

00:24:27.470 --> 00:24:27.710 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: Yeah.

00:24:27.710 --> 00:24:28.510 align:middle line:90%


00:24:28.510 --> 00:24:31.040 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: That thing was
charged, people in New York

00:24:31.040 --> 00:24:34.490 align:middle line:84%
could read the newspaper at 3
