>>ADAIR: Yes, very small.

00:28:54.860 --> 00:28:56.193 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We've been lucky there.

00:28:56.193 --> 00:28:59.220 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: And our planet,
which not every planet has it,

00:28:59.220 --> 00:29:01.980 align:middle line:84%
but our planet has
a radiation belt.

00:29:01.980 --> 00:29:06.540 align:middle line:84%
It's got multiple layers of
atmosphere, and it protects us.

00:29:06.540 --> 00:29:09.945 align:middle line:84%
And we're just the right
distance away from the sun

00:29:09.945 --> 00:29:11.280 align:middle line:90%
to withstand this.

00:29:11.280 --> 00:29:16.650 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: Now, an EMP, and
Electromagnetic Pulse,

00:29:16.650 --> 00:29:19.630 align:middle line:84%
is from a nuke detonated
in the atmosphere.

00:29:19.630 --> 00:29:20.430 align:middle line:90%
Correct?

00:29:20.430 --> 00:29:21.630 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Correct.

00:29:21.630 --> 00:29:25.830 align:middle line:84%
When the cyclotrons are
spinning on the nuclear weapon

00:29:25.830 --> 00:29:29.280 align:middle line:84%
and they detonate, they send
down an electromagnetic pulse

00:29:29.280 --> 00:29:30.420 align:middle line:90%
wave.

00:29:30.420 --> 00:29:32.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's the thing
does all the damage.

00:29:32.290 --> 00:29:33.150 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: All right.

00:29:33.150 --> 00:29:33.840 align:middle line:90%
Frightening.

00:29:33.840 --> 00:29:35.256 align:middle line:10%
>>ADAIR: The way
we found out-- we

00:29:35.256 --> 00:29:38.880 align:middle line:10%
didn't know anything about
an EMP until Project Orange.

00:29:38.880 --> 00:29:42.660 align:middle line:10%
That's when we fired missiles
off the back of a ship

00:29:42.660 --> 00:29:44.640 align:middle line:10%
in the middle of
the Pacific, and we

00:29:44.640 --> 00:29:47.880 align:middle line:10%
detonated nuclear weapons
in space at night.

00:29:47.880 --> 00:29:49.440 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: And what happened?

00:29:49.440 --> 00:29:52.050 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: We knocked out
the entire Indonesian

00:29:52.050 --> 00:29:53.606 align:middle line:90%
coast of power.

00:29:53.606 --> 00:29:54.480 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We did that?

00:29:54.480 --> 00:29:55.500 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: We did that, and--

00:29:55.500 --> 00:29:56.610 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: We kept that quiet.

00:29:56.610 --> 00:29:58.620 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: We sure did,
because we didn't know we

00:29:58.620 --> 00:29:59.828 align:middle line:90%
didn't know if we did or not.

00:29:59.828 --> 00:30:02.280 align:middle line:84%
People went, were we
responsible for that?

00:30:02.280 --> 00:30:04.290 align:middle line:84%
And that's when they
found out that--

00:30:04.290 --> 00:30:04.740 align:middle line:90%
>>NOORY: That's what happens.

00:30:04.740 --> 00:30:05.686 align:middle line:84%
>>ADAIR: --there's EMPs
coming off the thing.

00:30:05.686 --> 00:30:07.260 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: It's a
trickle-down effect.

00:30:07.260 --> 00:30:09.240 align:middle line:84%
Former Speaker of the
House Newt Gingrich,

00:30:09.240 --> 00:30:12.040 align:middle line:84%
which I think you presented
some information to--

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:12.840 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yeah.

00:30:12.840 --> 00:30:14.970 align:middle line:84%
>>NOORY: --was a
proponent on trying to get

00:30:14.970 --> 00:30:16.170 align:middle line:90%
this thing taken care of.

00:30:16.170 --> 00:30:17.736 align:middle line:90%
>>ADAIR: Yes.

00:30:17.736 --> 00:30:19.840 align:middle line:90%
>> Newt Gingrich!

00:30:19.840 --> 00:30:22.480 align:middle line:10%
>> Asked during the debate to
name the security threats that

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:25.600 align:middle line:10%
worry him, Newt Gingrich
lays out three scenarios.

00:30:25.600 --> 00:30:28.930 align:middle line:10%
A weapon of mass destruction
in an American city, a cyber

00:30:28.930 --> 00:30:31.177 align:middle line:10%
attack, and something
many have never heard of.

00:30:31.177 --> 00:30:33.010 align:middle line:10%
>>NEWT GINGRICH:
Electromotive pulse attack,

00:30:33.010 --> 00:30:35.230 align:middle line:10%
which would literally destroy
the country's capacity

00:30:35.230 --> 00:30:36.030 align:middle line:10%
to function.

00:30:36.030 --> 00:30:38.980 align:middle line:10%
>> An Electromagnetic
Pulse Attack, or EMP.

00:30:38.980 --> 00:30:43.660 align:middle line:10%
It's been the stuff of
fiction on the Fox show 24

00:30:43.660 --> 00:30:46.750 align:middle line:10%
but it's also a real threat
experts say it likely

00:30:46.750 --> 00:30:49.660 align:middle line:10%
wouldn't look like that
EMP attack, they say,

00:30:49.660 --> 00:30:52.870 align:middle line:10%
is an intense burst of
electromagnetic radiation.

00:30:52.870 --> 00:30:55.300 align:middle line:10%
It can be triggered by
detonating a nuclear weapon

00:30:55.300 --> 00:30:56.800 align:middle line:10%
at high altitude.

00:30:56.800 --> 00:30:59.020 align:middle line:84%
A weapon that could be
launched by a rogue nation,

00:30:59.020 --> 00:31:01.630 align:middle line:84%
or a terrorist group
with access to it.

00:31:01.630 --> 00:31:03.970 align:middle line:10%
Detonated low to the
ground, atomic weapons

00:31:03.970 --> 00:31:06.100 align:middle line:10%
have a devastating
physical shock.

00:31:06.100 --> 00:31:08.380 align:middle line:10%
But detonated miles
up in the atmosphere,

00:31:08.380 --> 00:31:11.380 align:middle line:10%
experts say the main
impact is electrical.

00:31:11.380 --> 00:31:13.510 align:middle line:10%
Energy that doesn't
kill people, but spreads

00:31:13.510 --> 00:31:17.020 align:middle line:10%
like lightning, striking any
electrical grid or circuitry.

00:31:17.020 --> 00:31:19.270 align:middle line:10%
Feeding into them,
burning them out.

00:31:19.270 --> 00:31:21.070 align:middle line:10%
Whole cities could go dark.

00:31:21.070 --> 00:31:25.180 align:middle line:10%
Security analyst James Carafano
has written about EMP attacks.

00:31:25.180 --> 00:31:27.100 align:middle line:10%
In one single event,
what could be disabled?

00:31:27.100 --> 00:31:30.010 align:middle line:10%
>> JAMES CARAFANO: If you
had a large-scale EMP event

00:31:30.010 --> 00:31:31.862 align:middle line:10%
in the United
States, you would--

00:31:31.862 --> 00:31:33.070 align:middle line:10%
everything would be disabled.

00:31:33.070 --> 00:31:35.950 align:middle line:10%
Because even things that
weren't knocked out-- let's

00:31:35.950 --> 00:31:38.677 align:middle line:10%
say your car, which might be OK.

00:31:38.677 --> 00:31:40.510 align:middle line:10%
But the electrical grid
is going to be gone.

00:31:40.510 --> 00:31:42.730 align:middle line:10%
There's going to be no
way to do traffic lights.

00:31:42.730 --> 00:31:45.640 align:middle line:10%
There's going to be
no way to land ships.

00:31:45.640 --> 00:31:47.750 align:middle line:10%
There's no way to get
fuel to the gas stations

00:31:47.750 --> 00:31:48.550 align:middle line:10%
to refill your car.

00:31:48.550 --> 00:31:50.200 align:middle line:10%
And if you got them there,
the gas pumps wouldn't work.

00:31:50.200 --> 00:31:52.730 align:middle line:10%
>> Think of this fictional
attack in the movie

00:31:52.730 --> 00:31:53.530 align:middle line:10%
"Ocean's 11".

