00:31:59.180 --> 00:32:01.670 align:middle line:10%
on a much smaller,
less-threatening scale

00:32:01.670 --> 00:32:03.560 align:middle line:10%
at the University
of Maryland, showing

00:32:03.560 --> 00:32:06.260 align:middle line:10%
how magnetic fields from
some electronic devices

00:32:06.260 --> 00:32:08.470 align:middle line:10%
often interfere
with other devices.

00:32:08.470 --> 00:32:10.070 align:middle line:10%
>> You hear this
ringing behind me?

00:32:10.070 --> 00:32:11.960 align:middle line:10%
We're showing you what
electromagnetic interference

00:32:11.960 --> 00:32:12.760 align:middle line:10%
is.

00:32:12.760 --> 00:32:14.195 align:middle line:10%
Say this television is a car.

00:32:14.195 --> 00:32:17.065 align:middle line:10%
A car's function is
rolling along normally.

00:32:17.065 --> 00:32:18.890 align:middle line:10%
Here's a cell phone ringing.

00:32:18.890 --> 00:32:20.390 align:middle line:10%
When it gets close
to that, you can

00:32:20.390 --> 00:32:23.360 align:middle line:10%
see how the audio of the
television signal changes.

00:32:23.360 --> 00:32:25.160 align:middle line:10%
You can hear the interference.

00:32:25.160 --> 00:32:27.170 align:middle line:10%
That's essentially--
it's interfering

00:32:27.170 --> 00:32:28.610 align:middle line:10%
with the car's function.

00:32:28.610 --> 00:32:30.930 align:middle line:10%
>> But with a
large-scale EMP attack,

00:32:30.930 --> 00:32:32.990 align:middle line:10%
